Journal of Great Lakes Research

Volume 38, Issue 4, December 2012, Pages 585-599

A modeling study of ice–water processes for Lake Erie applying coupled ice-circulation models

Author links open overlay panel, Jia Wang b, , , ,
https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jglr.2012.09.021Get rights and content
Full text access

Abstract

A hydrodynamic model that includes ice processes and is optimized for parallel processing was configured for Lake Erie in order to study the ice–water coupling processes in the lake. A hindcast from April 2003 to December 2004 with hourly atmospheric forcing was conducted. The model reproduced the seasonal variation of ice cover, but the development of ice extent in January and its decay in March somewhat preceded the observations. Modeled lake circulation in ice-free seasons is consistent with previous studies for Lake Erie. Thermal structure of the lake was reasonably comparable to both satellite-derived observations and in-situ measurements, with mean differences ranging from − 2 °C to 4 °C, depending on the season. The impacts of ice–water stress coupling and basal melting of ice were examined based on numerical experiments. The results show that: 1) ice–water stress coupling significantly dampens the subjacent lake circulation in winter due to packed ice cover that slows down the surface water, and 2) basal melting of ice contributes to widespread ice cover in the lake. The demonstrated model validity could lead to further studies of ice–water processes in the lake, including interannual variation and impacts on ecosystems.

Highlights

► An ice-hydrodynamic coupled model was configured for Lake Erie through 2003–2004. ► Ice cover dampens the subjacent circulation because packed ice cover slows down the surface water. ► Basal melting of ice contributes to widespread ice cover in the lake.

Introduction

The presence of widespread ice cover on the Laurentian Great Lakes significantly influences lake effect storms, regional weather (Notaro et al., in press), the hydrologic cycle, water levels, the water temperature, and the circulation of the lakes. The Great Lakes are partially covered with ice from December to April. Initially, ice begins to form in shallow bays (e.g. landfast ice) and then gradually grows offshore. Maximum ice extent is normally observed in late January to late February, when ice typically covers from 24% of Lake Ontario to 90% of Lake Erie (Assel et al., 1983). Naturally-formed ice thickness in the lake can vary from a few centimeters to a meter or more (Rondy, 1976). Ice begins to decay and breakup in March.
Ice cover inhibits direct lake–atmosphere interaction, which influences the heat and momentum flux (which in turn changes water and air temperatures), and dampens wave action (Wang et al., 2010). For example, recent observations of sensible and latent heat fluxes over Lake Erie (Gerbush et al., 2008) show a rapid decrease in flux magnitude as ice concentration approaches 100%. Ice melting in spring is important for phytoplankton and zooplankton blooms (Kerfoot et al., 2011). Vanderploeg et al. (1992) suggested that an under-ice bloom in Lake Michigan was caused by high incident photosynthetically active radiation due to little snow on the ice, and possibly by water column stability due to the ice cover's shutdown of wind mixing.
An accurate lake–ice model is important for understanding the impacts of ice cover on the lakes. Regional climate and the lake's ecosystem are tied to lake ice cover, so knowledge of ice processes is essential for accurate operational lake models. Relatively short-term forecasts of lake ice are also important for regional weather forecasts to determine the surface boundary conditions of heat flux and evaporation. Accurate forecasts of the extent, duration, and thickness of ice in the Great Lakes are valuable in determining the closing and opening of waterways, and the operation and planning of icebreaking in shipping lanes. Winter recreationalists (including ice fishers) are noted as a secondary constituency for ice forecasts.
There have been several lake–ice modeling studies of the Great Lakes. Wake and Rumer (1983) conducted ice flow modeling for Lake Erie, with ice dynamics based on viscous-plastic rheology (Hibler, 1979). Their model was the first dynamic Great Lakes ice forecast model. External forcing was idealized as zero water current, a periodically rotating wind, and a constant ice melt rate. A follow-up study by Chieh et al. (1983) used more realistic wind fields based on land-based measurements. The melt rate as a function of air temperature was also taken into account. Their model also included wind-driven circulation by stipulating that the circulation is driven by wind only in the ice-free area. They did not however include ice–water stress coupling. Wang et al. (2010) pioneered coupled lake–ice modeling in the Great Lakes by applying the Great Lakes Ice-circulation Model (GLIM) to Lake Erie. They performed a hindcast from April 2003 to December 2004 with a spatial resolution of 2 km, reproducing the seasonal variation of ice cover as well as the water surface temperature. While Wang et al. (2010) were successful in introducing ice processes to the hydrodynamic model, their model did not include explicit ice–water stress coupling. Basal melting was also excluded from their model. The most recent study by White et al. (2012) applied a Regional Oceanic Modeling System that includes a dynamic and thermodynamic ice model and a biochemical model to Lake Superior. Their model uses a bulk formulation of ice–water heat transfer that causes basal melting, and also includes ice–water stress coupling. Their model successfully reproduced the observed long-term warming of water surface temperature, and showed that the annual gross primary production correlated positively with mean annual temperature and negatively with mean winter ice-cover magnitude. In Lake Erie, which is usually fully ice-covered (unlike Lake Superior), ice cover could have stronger influences on physical structure (e.g. thermal structure and circulation), as well as on biochemical processes. The thermodynamic features can significantly affect the accuracy of ecosystem modeling (White et al., 2012), and hence, the physical impacts of ice cover in Lake Erie need to be studied in order to improve future forecast models and ecosystem studies.
The mechanical ice and water flows are closely coupled, since ice motion modifies the momentum flux due to wind stress forcing to the water surface (Leppäranta, 2005). In Lake Erie, where the water surface is covered with ice in winter, the circulation underneath should be affected by ice motion. In the packed ice condition, ice internal stress in this study is modeled based on viscosity and plasticity and may dominate in the momentum equation, such that ice motion is damped and so is the lake circulation. Otherwise, if wind stress still dominates, wind-driven ice drift could increase the net stress to the water surface due to ice cover's rough surface (i.e. larger drag coefficient). Such modifications of surface stress by ice cover may change the circulation as well as the depth of the mixed-layer. In Wang et al. (2010) and Chieh et al. (1983), the surface stress is empirically approximated by the wind stress and ice concentration, and therefore, their models do not take into account the ice–water stress coupling. This weakness in previous studies motivates us to conduct numerical experiments with and without ice–water stress coupling to investigate the impacts on the lake circulation below the ice cover.
Ice melting can occur at the top, bottom, and sides of an ice block. Direct heating from incoming shortwave radiation causes melting at the top and sides, while basal melting, which occurs due to heat imbalance at the ice bottom, is dominated by ice–water heat transfer over warm water. While surface melting is generally significant as direct atmospheric heating including solar radiation mainly causes it, basal melting can be also significant in spring. Once the ice begins to retreat, the newly created open water absorbs the incoming shortwave radiation more effectively because of the lower albedo of the water surface, accelerating ice melting (i.e. ice–ocean albedo feedback, Austin and Colman, 2007, Hu and Wang, 2010, Nihashi et al., 2011, Wang et al., 2005, Wang et al., 2009). It is expected that ice retreat should be decelerated by the absence of basal melting. On the other hand, basal melting can cool down the surface water, even if the water surface is insulated from winter air by ice cover. This cool down due to the ice–water heat transfer (and resulting basal melting) may control ice extent, since the cooled surface water can easily re-freeze once it is exposed to the winter air. While the thermodynamics associated with basal melting could greatly influence ice extent, spring blooms, and possibly under-ice blooms (Vanderploeg et al., 1992), no previous lake–ice modeling study examined basal melting of ice. Here we also examine the impacts of basal melting.
We apply a parallelized ice-circulation model to Lake Erie, which is the shallowest of the five Great Lakes and is most affected by the winter freezing, using a similar configuration to Wang et al. (2010). The parallelized hydrodynamic model coupled with a two-dimensional ice model (ICEPOM) is chosen for computational efficiency, especially for the future massive numerical simulations that might cover the entire Great Lakes. Four model runs, which are listed in Table 1, are conducted in this study. The first experiment is “standard”, which includes both the ice–water stress coupling and basal melting. The “standard” model results are compared with the observations. The second experiment is “no ice–water stress coupling”, which is done to evaluate how the empirical formula used in Wang et al. (2010) that excluded the ice–water stress coupling could be valid or erroneous in predicting the ice extent and the lake circulation. The third is “no basal melting”, which is done to evaluate the impacts of basal melting on ice extent and thermal structure in the lake. We also ran the case “GLIM” as the fourth experiment, where the ice–water stress coupling and basal melting were added to the model by Wang et al. (2010).

Model

Lake–ice models

The computational domain includes all of Lake Erie (Fig. 1). ICEPOM, a three-dimensional hydrostatic ocean model with the Boussinesq approximation based on the Princeton Ocean Model (Mellor et al., 2002), is used for the numerical simulations. The model includes the level 2.5 turbulence closure parameterization (Mellor and Yamada, 1982), with a wave-breaking model as the surface boundary condition (Craig and Banner, 1994). Horizontal diffusion is calculated with a Smagorinsky eddy diffusion parameterization. There are no heat and volume fluxes from the coastal boundary. The model does not take into account tidal forcing. The hydrodynamic model is coupled with a two-dimensional ice model. The coupled model is basically identical to that of Fujisaki et al., 2010, Fujisaki et al., 2011 except that ice collision rheology is not included in this study. Distributed-memory parallelization is employed for the model using the message-passing interface. Depths used in the 2 km grid are derived from NOAA's three arc second raster bathymetry for Lake Erie (http://www.ngdc.noaa.gov/mgg/greatlakes/erie.html) by averaging values within each 2 km grid square. The bottom drag coefficient is calculated by assuming a logarithmic bottom boundary layer with a roughness length of 1 cm. A sigma coordinate is used in the vertical direction with 21 levels. The time steps for the hydrodynamic model are 20 s for the external mode (vertically uniform flow) and 300 s for the internal mode (flow with vertical structure). The time steps for the ice processes are 30 s for ice dynamics and 300 s for ice thermodynamics.
The ice dynamic model employs the elastic–viscous–plastic rheology of Hunke and Duckowicz (1997), with one category of ice thickness for each cell. The QUICKEST scheme (Leonard, 1979) is used for the advection of ice volume (i.e. concentration, thickness). Redistribution of the ice area and thickness is calculated in a semi-Lagrangian scheme: a sub-grid ice area in a rectangular shape is defined in each cell as well as velocities on the four sides. After one advection step, a new sub-grid ice area is calculated so that ice area, volume, and momentum are conserved. The momentum equation for ice motion is,(1)∂u→i∂t+f→×u⇀i=τ→aiρihi−τ→iwρihi−g∇η+∇⋅Σ¯where ρi, ui, and hi are the density of ice, the ice velocity, and the ice thickness, respectively. Topped arrows denote a vector. On the left side, the first term is the time derivative of ice velocity, and the second term is the Coriolis force, where f is the Coriolis parameter. On the right side, the first two τ terms denote air–ice stress and ice–water stress, respectively. The third term is the sea surface tilt force, where g is gravitational acceleration. The last term is the divergence of the ice internal stress, and Σ = σij is a tensor of the ice internal stress, which is based on the elastic–viscous–plastic rheology of Hunke and Duckowicz (1997). Details of the ice dynamic model and its parameters are given in Appendix A.
The air–ice stress τ→ai (the wind stress on the ice) and ice–water stress τ→iw are calculated by the following bulk formulas.(2)τ→ai=ρaCDai|u→a−u→i|u→a−u→i(3)τ→iw=ρwCDiwu→i−u→wu→i−u→wwhere u→a and u→w are vectors of wind speed and surface water current speed, respectively. ρa and ρw are the densities of air and water, respectively. CDai and CDiw are the air–ice and ice–water drag coefficients respectively. In this study, CDai is a function of ice thickness hi [m],(4)CDai=CDai01−exp−5hiwhere CDai0 is set to 2.3 × 10− 3 and CDiw is determined so that CDai/CDiw = 0.33 based on the geostrophic reference range from 0.19 to 0.8 (Leppäranta, 2005).
When a cell is covered with ice at concentration A, the net stress at the water surface τ→w is,(5)τ→w=τ→iwA+τ→aw1−Awhere the air–water stress τ→aw is given in a similar way to τ→ai,(6)τ→aw=ρaCDaw|u→a−u→w|u→a−u→w.
In Eq. (6), CDaw is the air–water drag coefficient, which is based on Large and Pond (1981). In Wang et al. (2010), the ice–water stress is empirically estimated based on the wind stress. The empirical method approximates the stress under ice as half of the wind stress, and therefore the net stress is:(7)τ→w=τ→aw1−0.5A.
This method does not explicitly contain the ice–water stress interaction described in Eqs. (3), (5). In “standard”, Eqs. (3), (5) are used to take into account the ice–water stress coupling. We also conduct an experiment “no ice–water stress coupling”, by using Eq. (7).
The ice thermodynamic model is similar to Parkinson and Washington (1979) with the 0-layer ice thermodynamics (Semtner, 1976), except that snow cover is not taken into account in our model. The in-situ measurements during 2010–2011 recorded 0 to 1 in. of snow cover on the ice, while the shoreline measurements in 1960s–1970s recorded 0 to 9 in. (George Leshkevich, personal communication). The exclusion of snow cover may result in less ice growth in the model, as snow cover generally has higher albedo and reduces the absorption of shortwave radiation. Appendix B provides details of the sensible, latent and shortwave heat fluxes. The ice surface temperature is determined as a result of the heat balance at the ice surface. New ice forms when the surface water is super-cooled (i.e. below 0 °C). Ice melting is formulated in three ways: surface melting when the ice surface temperature reaches the fusion point; lateral melting (Ohshima and Nihashi, 2005, Wang et al., 2009) that is caused by a certain fraction of shortwave radiation onto the open water; and basal melting due to the heat imbalance between the conductive heat and the ice–water heat transfer at the ice bottom. The parameterizations are those of Parkinson and Washington (1979).
Basal melting Δh at the thermodynamic time step Δt is formulated as follows:(8)Δh=−κiTsfc−Tbtm/hi+HblfΔtwhere Tsfc and Tbtm are temperatures at the top and bottom surface of ice, respectively. Tbtm is approximated as the freezing temperature here. κi is set to 2.04 W/m/K, denoting the heat conductivity of ice. lf is the latent heat of ice fusion. The ice–ocean heat transfer Hb is calculated by the bulk formula.(9)Hb=ρwcpwChu*Tbtm−Twwhere ρw and cpw are the density of water and the specific heat of water, respectively. The heat transfer coefficient Ch is set as 0.005 (McPhee et al., 2008), and u⁎ and Tw denote the friction velocity and the water surface temperature respectively. Warmer surface water temperature causes higher ice–water heat transfer (due to the larger temperature difference), resulting in faster melting on the ice bottom. Thus, advection of ice to areas of warmer surface water can cause fast basal melting that in turn causes significant cooling of the surface water. We conduct another numerical experiment “no basal melting”, where basal melting is turned off by disabling the ice–water heat transfer at the ice bottom (i.e. Hb = 0). The impact of basal melting is discussed in Impacts of basal melting section.
GLIM, which is used in the fourth experiment, is based on an updated model from Wang et al. (2010). The hydrodynamic part is similarly based on the Princeton Ocean Model, and the ice dynamic model employs the classical viscous–plastic rheology with a downwind difference for the Eulerian advection (Hibler, 1979). In GLIM, multi-category ice thickness distribution (Thorndike et al., 1975) is used with ten categories of ice thickness in a cell (0, 0.02, 0.05, 0.1, 0.2, 0.3, 0.4, 0.6, 0.8, 1.4 m). Similar to ICEPOM, a logarithmic bottom boundary layer is assumed for calculating the bottom drag coefficient, with a roughness length that varies from 2 cm in shallow water to 1 mm in deep water. The air–water drag coefficient is calculated as a function of stratification of the atmospheric boundary layer (Liu and Schwab, 1987, Schwab and Bedford, 1999, Wang et al., 2010). Note that in this study, the ice–water coupling processes are implemented in GLIM, such that it includes lateral and basal melting of ice and the ice–water stress coupling. Although we do not present the differences of the GLIM results by adding the ice–water coupling process, the results are quite similar to those that are observed in the experiments using ICEPOM.

Data

Hourly atmospheric forcing are wind speed at 10 m height, surface air temperature, dew point, and cloud fraction, which are based on surface meteorological measurements around Lake Erie. The 29 stations used include those from the National Data Buoy Center and the Coastal Marine Automated Network (Wang et al., 2010). The station data are interpolated into the model grid based on an objective analysis (Schwab and Bedford, 1999), with an update of a spatial interpolation technique (the “natural neighbor” interpolation, Beletsky et al., 2003).
The Great Lakes Surface Environmental Analysis (GLSEA) of surface water temperature is utilized to evaluate the model results. The data is produced by the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration/Great Lakes Environmental Research Laboratory/CoastWatch Program. The water surface temperature is based on the Advanced Very High Resolution Radiometer (AVHRR) imagery. Note that the water surface temperature below ice cover is approximated by the freezing temperature, i.e. 0 °C. Ice concentration is taken from the National Ice Center's Great Lakes Ice Analysis charts, which are based on Radarsat-2, Envisat, AVHRR, Geostationary Operational and Environmental Satellites (GOES), and Moderate Resolution Imaging Spectroradiometer (MODIS). The spatial resolution for the ice analysis is about 2.5 km. The modeled thermal structure in the summer of 2004 is also evaluated using temperature measurement data from the International Field Years on Lake Erie (IFYLE, Hawley et al., 2006). The ice thickness measurements from 1966 to 1979 are from the Great Lakes ice thickness database, which is available at the National Snow and Ice Data Center. The stations for the ice thickness measurements are shown in Fig. 1.

Model results

Model validation

Seasonal variation of ice cover
Fig. 2 shows the modeled and observed ice concentration for January to April 2004. The modeled values are daily averaged, and the observed values are interpolated to the model grid. In early January, ice started to form first in the western basin and the southern coastal region of the central basin. ICEPOM captures this early stage of ice formation, although the model over-estimates some ice formation along the northeastern coast. In February, the lake was almost fully covered with ice, with a band of slightly lower ice concentration (~ 70%) in the western and northern parts of the central basin. The modeled ice extent is also high, but the area of lower ice concentration is not simulated. There are narrow polynyas (i.e. open water region) of 2–6 km along the coast in the model results. The observed ice cover, which shows a relatively large open water area along the southern coast, does not show the smaller polynyas in the other areas. Not modeling landfast ice in this study may be the cause of these polynyas. In March, ice retreated quickly due to increasing solar radiation in spring. Ice cover persisted in the northern region longer than in the southern region. This is consistent with the northern region's larger heat capacity due to its greater depth that slowed down the warming of surface water compared with the shallower southern region. The model reproduces this retreat, although there is an opening along the northern coast that was not observed, and the modeled ice cover extends further south in the central basin than observed. In April, ice cover almost disappears except for a very small amount of ice along the southern coast of the eastern basin, which is reproduced reasonably by the model.
Overall, the model reproduces the seasonal variation of ice extent (Fig. 3) reasonably well, but over-predicts late-January ice cover and predicts a faster retreat from late March to early April than was observed. This suggests that the model may under-estimate the heat capacity of the lake. It is also possible that the mixed layer depth might be under-estimated both in winter and spring, so that the heat capacity is under-predicted, resulting in faster lateral melting and cooling. The root mean square errors of ice extent are 2.9 × 103 km2 (“standard”), 3.6 × 103 km2 (“no basal melting”), and 3.6 × 103 km2 (“GLIM”). The values from “no ice–water stress coupling” are not shown, since they are almost identical to the values from “standard.”
“No basal melting” gives a slightly slower retreat of ice in spring, which is not unexpected. On the other hand, maximum ice extent in February in the “no basal melting” case is smaller than that in the “standard” case. We believe this can be explained by the re-distribution of heat due to ice–water heat transfer, which is described in Ice–water stress interaction section.
“GLIM” also reproduces the seasonal variation of ice extent reasonably well, but the ice concentration is much more diffuse in the spring melting season (Fig. 4). Such diffusion is possibly due to numerical diffusion caused by the GLIM's Eulerian advection scheme A similar issue can be identified in the ice extent during the melting season in Wang et al. (2010, Fig. 5 in their paper). Through the simulation period, the ice edge modeled by ICEPOM is sharper than that in “GLIM”, and is closer to the observed ice edge. The ability to predict such a sharp ice edge may be a benefit of the semi-Lagrangian redistribution scheme, which avoids the undesired numerical diffusion in a cell that is caused by cell averaging of sub-grid scale ice areas.
Ice thickness
Unfortunately, ice thickness measurements are not available during this period to compare with the model results. The modeled ice thickness is within the range of 0–50 cm, except for some coastal points where ice thickness locally exceeds 1 m. This thick ice may be due to local ice convergence that causes mechanical ridging and results in an increase in thickness.
Monthly frequencies and mean values of ice thickness are shown in Table 2. The values from the “no ice–water stress coupling” case are not shown in Table 2, because the differences from the “standard” case values are small (less than 1 cm). The thicknesses are mean values over a computational cell. In the “standard” case, mean ice thickness attains a maximum value (20.9 cm) in February and declines in March. Note that the open water cells are excluded in the average. Hence, the large value in April (23.5 cm) corresponds to the thick ice that survives melting until April. For reference, monthly mean ice thicknesses from Great Lakes ice thickness database during 1966–1979 are 20.7 cm (113) in January, 27.8 cm (128) in February, 21.5 cm (87) in March, and 5.3 cm (3) in April (digits in the parentheses are the number of measurements). These values are comparable to the modeled values. However, they are from a different set of years, and in addition, the observations are from the coastal station data, not 2 km × 2 km cell averages. They are probably not representative of the lake-wide mean. Further comparison of lake ice thickness should be pursued in future studies with a temporally synchronized comparison of model results and observations.

“No basal melting” shows larger mean ice thickness in January by 2.4 cm, which is 22% more than the “standard” result. This difference could be significant in the sense that basal melting could control the mean ice thickness in early winter. In the other months, the difference is less significant. Monthly mean values from “GLIM” are larger than those from “standard” in January and February, while they are smaller in March and April.
Fig. 5 shows monthly histograms of lake-wide average ice thickness. The shapes of “standard” and “no basal melting” are similar, while those of “GLIM” are different from the other experiments. The histograms from “GLIM” show detached peaks around 0.3 m in February and 0.15–0.2 m in March, which are likely produced by the multi-category thickness distribution model used in GLIM.
Note that the time series of total ice volume are quite similar among all the numerical experiments, except that from late March to April, GLIM shows a faster decline of ice volume (not shown).
Lake circulation
Fig. 6 shows the stream functions for vertically-averaged lake circulation averaged through three months from “standard.” A stream function ϕ is defined as ϕ=−∫u¯dyor∫v¯dx, where ū and v¯ are vertically averaged velocities in x and y directions, respectively. It has been shown that the net transport in the lake was mainly wind-driven with limited vertical shear (Bennet, 1974, Saylor and Miller, 1987). The clockwise and anti-clockwise gyres in the model results were almost consistent with the negative and positive wind stress curl in spring and summer, respectively. In fall and winter, a two-cell pattern of circulation was dominated due to the strong westerly wind (Bennet, 1974).
In April–June, the circulation is anti-clockwise over the basin except along the northern coast where the stream functions are weakly positive (clockwise circulation). In July–September, anti-clockwise gyres are observed in the western-central and the eastern basins. In the central basin, the flow is weakly clockwise. Such a pattern is common for both years, and consistent with the model results of May–October in 1994 (Schwab et al., 2009) and the available observations (Beletsky et al., 1999). Our model results show an anti-clockwise gyre during summer, which is consistent with Leon et al. (2005), however, our results do not confirm the clockwise gyre in the west-central basin simulated in their study. The anti-clockwise gyre in the northern basin is possibly caused by the topography (Fig. 1), as the flow tends to be parallel to isobaths in the quasi-geostrophic state.
In October–December, the modeled circulations are characterized by two east-and-west elongated gyres: a clockwise gyre along the northern coast and an anti-clockwise gyre in the southwest part. This is consistent with the winter observations during 1979–1980 (Beletsky et al., 1999). The two-gyre pattern in winter is likely due to the stronger westerly wind, which establishes a northeastward flow along the coastal region, where the water column is shallow and hence responds to wind faster than in the deeper region. The compensating southwestward flow occurs in the middle of the lake.
In January–March, the modeled circulation is rather weak. This is likely because (as we discuss in Ice–water stress interaction section) the heavy ice cover dampens the wind stress on the water surface. Since the flow patterns of “no basal melting” and “GLIM” are similar to that of the “standard” case, they are not shown.
Water temperature in ice-free seasons
Fig. 7 shows the 2004 water surface temperature in the middle of May, July, September, and November from the model and the satellite-derived observation. On May 15th, significant warming was observed in the shallow coastal area due to increasing heat flux in spring (Fig. 7a). The model was successful in predicting this (Fig. 7b), but there is over-warming except for the far northeast region. Colder water still remains in the northeast (the deepest part of the lake) because of the larger heat capacity. At the eastern end of the northeast coast, the modeled surface temperature is less than the observed. The northeastward wind might drive advection of surface water excessively in the model. On July 15th, upwelling of cold water was observed along the northwestern coast due to the southwesterly wind. The coastal upwelling is captured in the model result, although the coastal region shows a cooler temperature than was observed. On September 15th, the surface temperature was more than 20 °C over most of the lake, and there was a region of relatively low temperature along the northeastern coast, possibly due to weak coastal upwelling by the northward wind. On November 15th, the surface temperature was much less than in September. The model under-predicts the surface temperature in the northern coastal region.
Fig. 8 shows a time series of the modeled and observed lake-wide mean surface temperatures and the differences between them. The temporal variation of the mean water surface temperature is reasonably simulated by the model, but the model tends to predict the warmer surface temperature in April–August by 0–4 °C than GLSEA's, and the cooler surface temperature in September–December by 0–2 °C. Several factors could cause this: a comparison of GLSEA temperature with the buoy measurements in the western Lake Erie through 1998–2000 by Niziol (2003) showed that GLSEA under-predicted the surface temperature in summer, and over-estimated in late-fall. It is possible that the GLSEA product is biased in our simulation period, too. Otherwise, the model simply over-estimates the amplitude of the heat fluxes, such as by over-estimation of the air–water heat exchange coefficient. The meteorological data itself could have an error and/or biases over the lake season by season, as they are mostly based on the coastal observations.
Fig. 9 shows a time-series of vertical profiles of the modeled water temperature at T12 and T15. The model reasonably predicts the thermocline development, but the modeled thermocline is diffuse compared with the observations. A too diffuse thermocline was also noticed in the Lake Michigan model by Beletsky and Schwab (2001), and Beletsky et al. (2006), who also used the Princeton Ocean Model as a hydrodynamic model. They suspected that steepening of internal waves in the model maybe artificially diffusing the thermocline. Comparing the temporal mean profiles through June–October in 2004 (Fig. 10), the model over-predicts the temperature profile except for at the bottom of the thermocline at T15. The over-warming under the thermocline could be due to a too strong vertical diffusion of temperature or the presence of offshore bottom Ekman transport that entrains the warm coastal surface water.

Ice–water stress interaction

Fig. 11 shows three-month means of stream functions and ice velocities for the “standard” and “no ice–water stress coupling” experiments. The water circulation is rather weak (maximum of 0.4 m2/s) during the ice-covered season in the “standard” experiment (January–March), because the heavy ice cover dampens wind-stress transmitted to the water surface. On the other hand, in “no ice–water stress coupling” experiment, the lake is still wind driven, even if it is fully ice-covered, resulting in stronger circulation (maximum of 0.6 m2/s). In “standard”, the ice velocity is reduced along the north and south coast by the ice–water stress coupling. It is likely that in this case, the coastal ice reduces the wind stress transmitted to the adjacent water. In “no ice–water stress coupling” experiment, both the ice cover and the water under the ice cover feel the wind stress directly. While the velocity fields show a noticeable difference between the two experiments, the seasonal variations of ice extent are similar. The circulations in and after April (not shown) are similar in the “standard” and the “no ice–water stress coupling” experiments, indicating that the effect of the stress coupling does not last to the ice-free season.

Impacts of basal melting

As expected, the “no basal melting” experiment shows a slower ice retreat in March and April (Fig. 3). The heated surface water increases heat transfer between the water surface and the ice bottom and significantly contributes to basal melting that leads to fast ice retreat. Interestingly, in the mid-winter, the “no basal melting” experiment shows a smaller peak of ice area than the “standard” experiment (Fig. 3). This is caused by the absence of cooling of the surface water due to the ice–water heat transfer in “no basal melting” experiment. Basal melting is accompanied by a cooling of surface water due to the loss of latent heat. When this cooled water is exposed to the winter air by advection of ice or of the surface water itself, it could freeze immediately. Hence, the heat distribution creates a favorable condition for greater ice extent in winter. The heat redistribution due to ice–water heat transfer has been noticed in marginal seas, such as the Sea of Okhotsk, where melting at the thermal front controls the ice extent (Fujisaki et al., 2010) although re-freezing may not be significant in the Sea of Okhotsk. Note that melting at the top and lateral surfaces is caused by the direct incidence of shortwave radiation and does not affect the ice–water heat transfer directly. In Fig. 3, the time series from the “no basal melting” experiment may appear to outperform those from the “standard” experiment in March–April, but it seems likely that some other deficiency of the model, such as under-estimation of heat capacity of the lake (i.e. under-estimation of the thermocline depth or the mixed layer depth), compensates for the impact of excluding basal melting.
Fig. 12 shows the spatial distribution of the ice concentration and water surface temperature on February 20, 2004. As is also seen in Fig. 3, the ice area is more extensive with basal melting, but at the same time, the water surface temperature is clearly lower. The heat flux at the water surface shows stronger cooling in the “standard” experiment in late January, due mostly to the ice–water heat transfer Hb (Fig. 13a). Accordingly, the mean water surface temperature of the “standard” experiment is lower from late January to March by more than 0.4 °C than that of the “no basal melting” experiment (Figs. 13b,c). Such cooling likely leads to new ice formation over the open water, which results in an increased ice area in February. Note that the volumetric production of ice (not shown) hardly changes regardless of the presence of basal melting. Basal melting contributes to wider and thinner ice extent in the lake in winter by the heat redistribution.

Discussion

The effects of the ice–water coupling processes revealed in this study, which past lake–ice studies have not focused on, can significantly influence not only physical conditions but also material transport in the lake including transport of biochemical materials. The damped circulation due to ice cover (Fig. 11) could influence how much the external phosphorus load from coastal inputs is carried toward the central basin. Low ice coverage in mild winters could lead to wider spreading of the phosphorus load, which would influence the concentration of nutrients in the following spring and summer. In addition to the impacts on the circulation, dampening of waves by ice cover could have other impacts on nearshore ecology, as ice is important for protecting whitefish eggs from damage and mortality caused by wave action in the Great Lakes and other northern lakes (Taylor et al., 1987, Vanderploeg et al., 1992). However, the model in this study does not include any material transport processes or a wave model. Further investigations are necessary to evaluate the impacts of ice cover on material transports and nearshore ecologies. The dampening of circulation and waves by ice cover is likely most significant in Lake Erie, since the other four lakes have relatively low annual ice coverage (Wang et al., 2010). However, ice typically starts to form along the coasts in all the Great Lakes where the dampening is most significant, so it is possible that coastal flows and material transports are significantly influenced by ice cover in all of the Great Lakes.
While basal melting significantly influences thermal structure and ice extent in Lake Erie, the impacts in the other Great Lakes leave room for further examination. The other four lakes have much larger heat storage due to their depth, and the associated heat flux across the thermocline may control the ice edge, unlike the case in Lake Erie. In Lake Erie, basal melting could also impact the lake's ecosystem. The wider spread of ice cover due to the re-distribution of heat could create a favorable condition for under-ice plankton blooms that can occur due to both the penetrating shortwave radiation across clear ice and the stratified water below ice (Vanderploeg et al., 1992).
We observe differences between the model results and the observations of the thermal structure in ice-free seasons. These include the overestimation (underestimation) of mean surface water temperature in summer (fall). This overestimation and underestimation imply that the actual surface heat storage is more than is modeled, or the modeled surface heat flux is more amplified than actual surface heat flux. Modeled ice extent increases more rapidly than the observed extent in January (developing season) and decreases more rapidly in March (melting season), as is shown in Fig. 3. This faster response of ice formation and decline also suggests the model's under-prediction of the heat storage, or over-prediction of the magnitude of the surface heat flux. There are several possibilities to explain this, such as the under-estimation of the thermocline depth and the over-estimation of the sensible heat flux, which is due to the over-estimation of the turbulent heat transfer coefficient or the air temperature being too warm (too cold) in summer (fall–early winter). Further investigation is necessary to improve the model performance.

Summary and conclusions

A high-resolution hydrodynamic model coupled with ice processes, ICEPOM, was configured for Lake Erie. A hindcast simulation from April 2003 to December 2004 was conducted using atmospheric forcings compiled based on surface meteorological measurements. The model reasonably reproduces the seasonal variation of ice cover, but the ice formation and ice melting somewhat precede the observed formation and melting. The modeled seasonal circulations are consistent with previous studies. In the ice-covered season (January–March), the circulation is relatively weak due to the presence of ice cover acting as a dampening mechanism. The model reasonably reproduces the thermal structure in the lake, while it over-predicts (under-predicts) the surface water temperature in April–August (September–December).
The impacts of the ice–water stress coupling and basal melting of ice were investigated based on the numerical experiments. The following conclusions can be drawn:
  • 1.
    Ice cover in the lake significantly dampens the lake circulation, and the ice velocity is reduced along the coast by the ice–water stress coupling. The coupling process occurs because the congested ice cover reduces the wind stress transmitted to the subjacent water. The dampening effect does not last into the ice–free season in Lake Erie.
  • 2.
    Basal melting of ice contributes to a thinner and wider ice extent in Lake Erie in winter as a result of heat redistribution. The ice–water heat transfer cools down the surface water close to the freezing temperature, and once the cooled surface water is exposed to the winter air, it is immediately super-cooled and freezes, resulting in a more extensive ice area. The heat redistribution process is an important process that helps to control ice extent in the lake.
Although the simulation period is limited to one year, this study shows the model's validity and the impacts of the ice–water coupling. Further simulations using an interannual time scale and application to the other lakes will provide useful information to increase our understanding of the ice–water processes in the lakes. One of the major concerns related to ice processes is to understand how it couples with material circulations and ecosystems in the Great Lakes. Blooms of zooplankton and phytoplankton in spring, as well as under-ice blooms, should be studied in association with ice conditions, for which the model can be utilized.

Appendix A.

The ice dynamics model in ICEPOM employs the elastic–viscous–plastic rheology of Hunke and Duckowicz (1997). The relation between the strain rate tensor ε˙ij and ice internal stress tensor σij is:(A-1)ε˙ij=1E∂σij∂t+12ησij+η−ζ4ηζσkkδij+P4ζδijwhere δij is Kronecker's delta. The first term on the right side denotes the elastic term, which is included in order for the internal stress field σij to be solved explicitly rather than as a physical requirement. E is the elastic modulus, which is set to 0.25. The shear viscosity η and the bulk viscosity ζ are given by:(A-2)η=ζe2(A-3)ζ=P2maxΔΔ0where e is the ratio of the normal stress to the shear stress and is set to 2. Δ=ε˙11+ε˙222+1/e2ε˙11−ε˙222+4/e2ε˙122 is a parameter of the strain rate with a lower limit Δ0 = 10− 7 s− 1. Compressive strength P is calculated based on Hibler (1979) and Wang et al. (1994):(A-4)P=P*Ahiexp−C1−Awhere A is ice concentration in a cell, and therefore, Ahi represents a mean ice thickness over a cell. P⁎ is a compressive strength of compact ice of unit thickness, which is set to 10 kPa in this study. A constant C, which is set to 20, gives the inverse of the e-folding scale for ice strength as a function of ice concentration.

Appendix B.

Here we describe the equations and parameters for the ice thermodynamics. The upward and downward longwave radiations are calculated based on black body emissions using the correction by Efimova (1961), and a cloud effect by Maykut and Church (1973).
The sensible heat flux, Hs, and the latent heat flux, Hl, are calculated by the bulk formulations:(B-1)Hs=ρaCscp|u→a|Ta−Tsfc(B-2)Hl=ρaClle|u→a|qa−qsfcwhere Cp is the specific heat of air. le is the latent heat of evaporation (2.5 × 106 J/kg) or the latent heat of sublimation (2.8 × 106 J/kg), depending on whether the surface is water or ice. Ta and Tsfc are the surface air temperature and the surface temperature of water or ice, respectively, where Tsfc is the diagnostic variable in the thermodynamic model. qa and qsfc are the specific humidity of the surface air and the water (or ice) surface, respectively. At the ice or water surface, the saturation vapor pressure is assumed and is calculated with the given air pressure and dew point, based on Murray (1967). Thus, qsfc is approximated as the saturation specific humidity. The sensible heat transfer coefficient Cs is set to 1.75 × 10− 3 for unstable state (Ta < Tw) and 0.875 × 10− 3 for stable state (Ta ≥ Tw). The latent heat transfer coefficient Cl is set to 1.75 × 10− 3.
The shortwave radiation is parameterized based on McCormick and Meadows (1988). Their formula is originally based on Cotton (1979) for the surface flux and their time-dependent coefficients are regression estimates for the observations in Lake Erie. The net radiation at the surface I(0) is:(B-3)Iclear=A0+A1cosZ+A2cos2Z+A3cos3ZI(0)=Iclear(0.999−0.425c+0.922c2−1.14c3)(1−αw,i)(B-4)αw=0.045/cosZwhere Iclear denotes the clear-sky solar radiation, and cosZ is the cosine of the zenith angle, c is the cloud fraction (0–1), and αw,i is the albedo of the water or ice surface. While the water surface albedo is defined as Eq. (B-4), the ice surface albedo is set to 0.7. The parameter A0 varies monthly such that A0 = (2.8, 10.3, 17.2, − 1.7, − 23.3, − 43.6, − 50, − 45.6, − 28.6, − 16.9, − 3.3, − 1.7) [W/m2]. A1, A2, and A3 are constants 683 W/m2, 836 W/m2, and − 486 W/m2, respectively. The vertical attenuation of the incoming shortwave radiation is parameterized following Paulson and Simpson (1977).(B-5)Iz=I0aexpz/l1+1−aexpz/l2where the coefficient a is 0.55. The attenuation lengths l1 and l2 for red and blue-green light respectively, are set to 0.35 m and 3.6 m. These settings reasonably reproduced the mixed-layer depth in Lake Erie (McCormick and Meadows, 1988).
